name: PAC-MAN Bookshelf with Light and Wheels
description:
Tall bookshelf handcrafted in pinewood with 4 compartments. 
The top part is a lightbox with original PAC-MAN video game marquee from 1980 as the front glass. The marquee is made of plexiglass and is in excellent vintage condition slightly worn out around the edges. The back side of the lightbox can be removed in order to replace the two bulbs. 
The bookshelf was given a light blue shade using water-based, high quality paints. The shelves are white and distressed to give them an unfinished look, so natural wood can be seen through the paint.
The bookshelf stands on 4 sturdy bright red wheels and features a light blue textile cord that holds switch and Europlug. 
Bulbs are not included. We recommend using high efficiency light bulbs when the back cover is closed.

Dimensions: L 62 cm x W 26 cm x H 172 cm  

----------------

PAC-MAN is pronounced “Pakkuman” in Japanese and written パックマン. The game was developed by Namco Ltd. and first released in Japan on May 22, 1980. It was licensed for distribution in the United States by Midway, in October 1980. 
Immensely popular from its original release to the present day, PAC-MAN is considered one of the classics of the medium, virtually synonymous with video games, and an icon of 1980s pop culture.

name: Orange Bundt Pan Tripod Floor Lamp
description:
Let them eat cake. - This original tripod floor lamp features a lampshade made of a heavy bundt cake mold. The mold is an original early 1960's Nordic Ware bund pan made of cast aluminum. Bright orange enamel shows some signs of use. The interior is coated with Teflon and holds two bulbs to keep away those under the bed monsters. 
Tripod legs are handcrafted in reclaimed oak wood from parts that used to form a century-old bed. An orange textile cord holds floor switch and Europlug. 
Bulbs are not included. We recommend using high efficiency light bulbs as they won’t heat up the lamp shade. 

Height: 120 cm
Lamp shade diameter: 27 cm

----------------

The person who popularized the Bundt cake is American businessman H. David Dalquist, co-founder of Nordic Ware. In around 1950, one Jewish-American society approached Dalquist asking if he could produce a modern version of a traditional ceramic Gugelhupf dish, a traditional European fruit cake. Nordic Ware made a small number of the pans trademarked under the name "Bundt". 
Initially, the Bundt pan sold so poorly that Nordic Ware considered discontinuing it. The product received a boost when it was mentioned in the New Good Housekeeping Cookbook in 1963, but did not gain real popularity until 1966 when a Bundt cake called the "Tunnel of Fudge" took second place at the annual Grand National Recipe and Baking Contest. The resulting scramble caused the Bundt pan to surpass the tin Jell-O mold to become the most-sold pan in the United States in the 1960s.

name: Bunny Rabbit Desk Lamp
description:
A large desk lamp with heavy concrete base. The unique lamp shade is made of an antique polished aluminum jelly mold in a shape of a bunny rabbit. A beautiful vintage piece featuring realistically styled slumbering rabbit. The mold is in an excellent vintage condition showing little use. Features mark “Swan Brand” by the English manufacturer. 
The flexible arm is made of reclaimed oak wood, using parts of a century-old bed. The butterfly nuts situated in the arm joints add to the piece some industrial flair. 
Bright red textile cord holds switch and Europlug. 
Bulb is not included. We recommend using high efficiency light bulb as it won’t heat up the lamp shade.

Height: 60 cm (in pictured position)

----------------

Bulpitt& Sons Ltd was a brass founders established in Birmingham in the latter part of the 19th century. The "Swan Brand" name was registered by Bulpitt& Sons Ltd in the early part of the 20th century and was primarily used for their domestic range of polished aluminum products like frying pans, kettles, tea sets and jelly molds. 
In the 1920s, Bulpitts moved into electrical appliances including kettles, irons, heaters and steamers. They pioneered the first electric element that could be immersed in water.The Swan brand continued its success throughout the next few decades and became synonymous with solid British manufacturing quality and innovation. There was a Swan branded product in virtually every home. 
Bulpitt& Sons (Swan Brand) Ltd was finally dissolved on 21st May 1989 - approximately 100 years after they were first established.

name: Mid-Century Style Chest of Drawers in Mint Green and Yellow
description:
Mid-Century style upcycled 1970’s chest of drawers with an underframe, made in Spain. Drawers made of solid wood, front panels made of plywood veneered with tropical wood Mahogany and Sapeli. The body made of plywood. 
The frame is painted asymmetrically in mint green and soft yellow, using water-based, high quality paints. 
2 thin drawers, 1 medium drawer and 1 large drawer. 

Dimensions: L 80 cm x W 40 cm x H 83 cm

name: Art Deco Style Crib with Japanese Fabric Mattress
description:
This original crib has been assembled using headboard and footboard of an antique 1920’s bed in Art Deco style. Both pieces are made of solid oak wood and have been distressed and moisturized with special eco-friendly oils to recover their original color and texture. 
The front and back panels are made of pinewood, painted in mint green and make a nice contrast with the antique parts of the furniture piece. 
3 big white cotton tassels in Victorian style adorn the geometric design of the antique pieces. 
Custom-made mattress is covered using Japanese fabric which has playful retro-style pattern showing china cups and teapots. 
The crib is shipped flat and is easy to assemble using 8 XL bolts (included). 

Dimensions: L 96 cm x W 57 cm x H 95 cm
Mattress dimensions: L 90 cm x W 50 cm x H 8 cm

name: ATARI Pole Position Book Shelve with Light and Wheels
description:
Tall bookshelf handcrafted in pinewood with 4 compartments. The top part is a lightbox with original ATARI Pole Position video game marquee from 1980's as the front glass. The glass marquee is in excellent vintage condition slightly worn around the edges. The back side of the lightbox can be removed in order to replace the two bulbs. 
The bookshelf is painted in matte black using water-based, high quality paints. The shelves are black and distressed to give them an unfinished look, so natural wood can be seen through the paint. 
The bookshelf stands on 4 bright red wheels. 
Fishbone BW textile cord holds floor switch and Europlug. 
Bulbs are not included. We recommend using high efficiency light bulbs when the back cover is closed.

Dimensions: L 63 cm x W 26 cm x H 170 cm 

----------------

The original Atari, Inc. was founded in 1972. It was a pioneer in arcade games, home video game consoles, and home computers. The company's products helped define the computer entertainment industry from the 1970s to the mid-1980s.
In Japanese, atari　(当たり, あたり, or アタリ) is the nominalized form of ataru （当たる, あたる, or アタル） (verb), meaning "to hit the target" or "to receive something fortuitously". The word "atari" is used in Japanese when a prediction comes true or when someone wins a lottery.

description:
Lovely vintage bedside lamp with red lampshade from 1970's covered with white polka dots. Reminds of a huge fly agaric! 
Composed of: a clear glass base, a plastic mid-section in mint green and an add-on plastic lamp shade. 
Fluor green textile cord holds switch and Europlug. 
Bulb is not included.

Height: 37 cm
Lamp shade diameter: 20 cm

name: “Tea for One” Bedside Lamp
description:
Small whimsical bedside lamp with a base made of vintage 1960’s "tea for one" teapot and cup set. 
The ceramic set features a large decal of 1930's style girl that covers both the cup and the pot. The adorable girl with big blue eyes is very busy with her chores: she is holding a watering can in one hand and some dirty dishes in the other. 
The lamp shade in ivory white has a wide yellow stripe that adds playfulness to the piece. 
Bright yellow textile cord holds switch and Europlug. 
Bulb is not included.

Height: 30 cm
Lamp shade diameter: 20 cm

name: Italian Vintage School Satchel in Dark Mint Green
description:
Original vintage school satchel made in Italy in early 1970's. Unused as was stored in a warehouse after closing a school supply store in Italy. 
Made of quality faux leather in dark mint green and dotted white. 
Original clasps in gold finish have a label “Made in Italy”. The pieces that secure the handle aside also feature a mark in the shape of the famous “Lo Stivale” (The Boot).  
Clear leather, easy to adjust shoulder straps were added. 
The satchel has two compartments. 
Not suitable for adults due to shoulder strap length.

Dimensions: L 40 cm x W 13 cm (max.) x H 30 cm
